<publication>
    <title>Visualizing the action of steroid hormone receptors in living cells</title>
    <authors>Griekspoor</authors>
    <source>Nucl Rec Sig</source>
    <reference>2007 vol. 4</reference>
    <id>E54D2995-7A7A-4DEE-AED3-00740C786E86</id>
    <annotations>
        <annotation>
            <text>Transcription controlled by Steroid Hormone Receptors (SHRs) plays a key role in many important physiological processes like organ development, metabolite homeostasis, and response to external stimuli.</text>
            <page>0</page>
            <created_at>2011-12-16 14:17:48 +0000</created_at>
            <rects>
                <rect>{{79.200000000000003, 637.44799999999998}, {460.89799885177609, 8.3250000000000455}}</rect>
                <rect>{{79.200000000000003, 626.19899999999996}, {390.38999972152715, 8.3250000000000455}}</rect>
            </rects>
        </annotation>
        <annotation>
            <text>As early as 1896, Thomas Beatson described that removal of the ovaries in advanced breast cancer patients often resulted in remarkable improvement [Beatson, 1896].</text>
            <page>0</page>
            <created_at>2011-12-16 14:17:51 +0000</created_at>
            <rects>
                <rect>{{79.200000000000003, 454.88400000000001}, {198.91799828624727, 8.3249999999999886}}</rect>
                <rect>{{79.200000000000003, 443.63499999999999}, {221.91699910831454, 8.3249999999999886}}</rect>
                <rect>{{79.200000000000003, 432.38600000000002}, {206.18099739074711, 8.3249999999999886}}</rect>
                <rect>{{79.200000000000003, 421.137}, {25.01999869537353, 8.3249999999999886}}</rect>
            </rects>
        </annotation>
        <annotation>
            <text>As it turned out, this receptor plays a key role in the development and maintenance of the sexual reproductive tissues, and therefore, as Beatson had discovered, in breast cancer as well.</text>
            <page>0</page>
            <created_at>2011-12-16 14:17:55 +0000</created_at>
            <rects>
                <rect>{{79.200000000000003, 322.14499999999998}, {204.19199829101564, 8.3249999999999886}}</rect>
                <rect>{{79.200000000000003, 310.89600000000002}, {221.94600000000003, 8.3249999999999886}}</rect>
                <rect>{{79.200000000000003, 299.64699999999999}, {211.21199884510042, 8.3249999999999886}}</rect>
                <rect>{{79.200000000000003, 288.39800000000002}, {86.939999761581433, 8.3249999999999886}}</rect>
            </rects>
        </annotation>
        <annotation>
            <text>Rapid and almost complete nuclear translocation following ligand addition is a common behavior observed for almost all SHRs (Figure 2, step 3). </text>
            <page>1</page>
            <created_at>2011-12-16 14:17:58 +0000</created_at>
            <rects>
                <rect>{{318.10399999999998, 463.63499999999999}, {221.92900026607521, 8.3249999999999886}}</rect>
                <rect>{{318.10399999999998, 452.38600000000002}, {221.9169998254776, 8.3249999999999886}}</rect>
                <rect>{{318.10399999999998, 441.137}, {110.04300000000001, 8.3249999999999886}}</rect>
            </rects>
        </annotation>
        <annotation>
            <text>Nuclear receptors that bind steroid hormones typically form homodimers (Figure 2, step 4).</text>
            <page>2</page>
            <created_at>2011-12-16 14:18:09 +0000</created_at>
            <rects>
                <rect>{{79.200000000000003, 121.22500000000001}, {214.80299855518342, 8.3250000000000028}}</rect>
                <rect>{{79.200000000000003, 109.976}, {143.49599619865421, 8.3250000000000028}}</rect>
            </rects>
        </annotation>
    </annotations>
